# Streaming with Tool Use in Claude

Great question—this is where things get nuanced. Let me break down the different approaches based on your needs.

## The Core Issue

When Claude makes a tool call, you have two fundamental choices:

1. **Stream everything** — see Claude's thinking *and* tool calls in real-time, but you must handle tool execution yourself
2. **Stream Claude's output only** — Claude finishes tool calling internally, you execute tools, then stream the response

The choice depends on whether you want **fine-grained tool streaming** (GA—see Claude's tool calls as they're generated) or traditional streaming.

---

## Option 1: Fine-Grained Tool Streaming (Recommended for Real-Time UX)

This is **GA now** (no beta header needed). Claude streams tool call parameters as they're generated, giving you real-time visibility into what tools Claude is invoking.

### Basic Pattern

```typescript
const response = await client.messages.stream({
  model: "claude-opus-4-6",
  max_tokens: 4096,
  tools: [
    {
      name: "web_search",
      description: "Search the web",
      input_schema: {
        type: "object",
        properties: {
          query: { type: "string" }
        },
        required: ["query"]
      }
    }
  ],
  messages: [
    { role: "user", content: "What's the latest Claude news?" }
  ]
})
  .on("text", (text) => console.log("Text:", text))
  .on("contentBlockStart", (event) => {
    if (event.content_block.type === "tool_use") {
      console.log(`🔧 Tool call starting: ${event.content_block.name}`);
    }
  })
  .on("contentBlockDelta", (event) => {
    if (event.delta.type === "input_json_delta") {
      // Tool input is being streamed in real-time
      console.log("Tool params:", event.delta.partial_json);
    }
  });

// After stream completes, handle tool calls
const finalMessage = await response.finalMessage();
```

### Handle Tool Execution in a Loop

```typescript
let messages = [
  { role: "user", content: "Search for Claude updates" }
];

while (true) {
  const response = await client.messages.stream({
    model: "claude-opus-4-6",
    max_tokens: 4096,
    tools: [/* your tools */],
    messages
  })
    .on("contentBlockStart", (event) => {
      if (event.content_block.type === "tool_use") {
        console.log(`Calling: ${event.content_block.name}`);
      }
    })
    .finalMessage();

  // Check if Claude wants to use tools
  if (response.stop_reason === "tool_use") {
    // Extract tool calls from response
    const toolResults = [];
    for (const block of response.content) {
      if (block.type === "tool_use") {
        // Execute the tool
        const result = await executeTool(block.name, block.input);
        toolResults.push({
          type: "tool_result",
          tool_use_id: block.id,
          content: JSON.stringify(result)
        });
        console.log(`✓ ${block.name} executed`);
      }
    }

    // Add assistant response and tool results to messages
    messages.push({ role: "assistant", content: response.content });
    messages.push({ role: "user", content: toolResults });
  } else {
    // Claude finished (stop_reason === "end_turn")
    // Extract and display final text
    for (const block of response.content) {
      if (block.type === "text") {
        console.log("Final answer:", block.text);
      }
    }
    break;
  }
}
```

**Why this works:**
- You see `contentBlockDelta` events with `input_json_delta` *as Claude types* the tool parameters
- Real-time visibility into tool calls without waiting for the full message
- You maintain control over tool execution

---

## Option 2: Programmatic Tool Calling (Lowest Latency)

**GA now**—call tools from within code execution without round-tripping to the API. Best when Claude uses code execution to call other tools.

```typescript
const response = await client.messages.create({
  model: "claude-opus-4-6",
  max_tokens: 4096,
  tools: [
    {
      name: "web_search",
      description: "Search the web",
      input_schema: { /* ... */ }
    },
    {
      name: "code_execution",
      description: "Run Python code",
      input_schema: { /* ... */ }
    }
  ],
  messages: [
    {
      role: "user",
      content: "Search for stock prices and calculate averages"
    }
  ]
});

// Inside Claude's code execution, it can call web_search directly
// No additional round-trip needed
```

**Example flow:**
1. Claude decides to call `code_execution`
2. Inside the Python code, Claude calls `web_search` tool
3. Results flow back into the same code block
4. Claude continues—no API round-trip

---

## Option 3: Traditional Streaming (No Tool Visibility)

If you just want to stream Claude's text responses and handle tool execution on your end:

```typescript
const response = await client.messages.stream({
  model: "claude-opus-4-6",
  max_tokens: 4096,
  tools: [/* your tools */],
  messages
})
  .on("text", (text) => {
    // Stream text as it arrives
    console.log(text);
  });

// After stream completes, check for tool calls
const message = await response.finalMessage();
if (message.stop_reason === "tool_use") {
  // Handle tool calls
}
```

**Limitation:** You don't see tool calls streaming in real-time—you only see text. Tool calls are built up in the background and revealed at the end.

---

## Comparison Table

| Approach | Real-Time Tool Visibility | Requires Loop | Latency | Best For |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Fine-grained streaming** | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes | Low | Chat interfaces, user feedback |
| **Programmatic tool calling** | ✅ Yes (via code) | ❌ No | Lowest | Complex chains, code-driven tasks |
| **Traditional streaming** | ❌ No | ✅ Yes | Low | Simple text responses |

---

